Exercise 1 â€“ Preparing your environment and installing Az PowerShell module
Task 1 â€“ Open the Azure portal

Launch Microsoft Edge.

Navigate to:

https://portal.azure.com


Sign in with the Azure account assigned to your training environment.

If Azure proposes a guided tour, select Skip.

Task 2 â€“ Install the Az module for PowerShell

Open PowerShell 7 (pwsh) as Administrator.

Check the version:

$PSVersionTable.PSVersion


Update PowerShell 7 to the latest version:

iex "& { $(irm https://aka.ms/install-powershell.ps1) }"


Restart PowerShell automatically:

Start-Process pwsh -Verb RunAs
exit


Set the execution policy:

Set-ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Scope CurrentUser


Confirm with Y.

Install the Az module:

Install-Module Az -Scope CurrentUser -Force


Connect to Azure:

Connect-AzAccount


Verify that your subscription appears:

Get-AzContext

ðŸ§ª Exercise 2 â€“ Using Azure Cloud Shell
Task 1 â€“ Create a resource group from Cloud Shell

In the Azure portal, open Cloud Shell.

Choose PowerShell mode.

Allow Azure to create the storage backend.

Once Cloud Shell is ready, run:

Get-AzSubscription


View existing resource groups:

Get-AzResourceGroup


Switch to Bash inside Cloud Shell:

az group list
az account show


Return to PowerShell:

New-AzResourceGroup -Name RG-Training-Europe -Location northeurope


Confirm:

Get-AzResourceGroup -Name RG-Training-Europe

ðŸ§ª Exercise 3 â€“ Deploying and managing Azure resources with PowerShell
Task 1 â€“ Create a Virtual Machine (new example, new names)

Generate credentials for the VM OS:

$cred = Get-Credential -Message "Enter admin username and password for VM Training01"


Define VM parameters:

$vmConfig = @{
    ResourceGroupName     = "RG-Training-Europe"
    Name                  = "VM-Training01"
    Location              = "northeurope"
    ImageName             = "Ubuntu2204"
    PublicIpAddressName   = "IP-Training01"
    Credential            = $cred
    Size                  = "Standard_B1ms"
    OpenPorts             = 22
}


Deploy the VM:

$vm = New-AzVM @vmConfig


Display important details:

$vm
$vm.OSProfile | Select-Object ComputerName, AdminUsername


Retrieve private and public IP addresses:

Get-AzNetworkInterface -ResourceGroupName "RG-Training-Europe" |
Select-Object -ExpandProperty IpConfigurations |
Select-Object Name, PrivateIpAddress

$pub = Get-AzPublicIpAddress -Name "IP-Training01" -ResourceGroupName "RG-Training-Europe"
$pub | Select-Object IpAddress, @{n="DNS";e={$_.DnsSettings.Fqdn}}


Connect via SSH (Linux example):

ssh <your-admin>@$($pub.IpAddress)

Task 2 â€“ Add a new disk to the VM

Get the VM object:

$vmObj = Get-AzVM -ResourceGroupName "RG-Training-Europe" -Name "VM-Training01"


Add a 10 GB data disk:

Add-AzVMDataDisk -VM $vmObj -Name "TrainingDisk01" -LUN 1 -DiskSizeInGB 10 -CreateOption Empty -Caching ReadWrite


Update the VM:

Update-AzVM -VM $vmObj -ResourceGroupName "RG-Training-Europe"

Task 3 â€“ Clean up Azure resources

Delete the entire resource group and all resources:

Remove-AzResourceGroup -Name "RG-Training-Europe" -Force

